In v5, `after` on a state declares a transition that fires automatically after a delay. Delays can be inline numbers or — more usefully — named strings that resolve against `setup.delays`. Declaring a delay there as `({ context }) => ms` makes it per-instance: two actors of the same machine can have different timings just by initializing their context differently. When the state is exited before the delay elapses, the scheduled transition is cancelled automatically.

