The nested form hid the reading order — with `pipe`, each transformation sits on its own line in the order it runs, which is also the order the reader expects.

```ts
import { pipe, flow } from 'fp-ts/function';

const inc = (n: number): number => n + 1;
const dbl = (n: number): number => n * 2;
const str = (n: number): string => `value=${n}`;

// Data-first: apply the composition to a concrete argument.
export const applyToTen: string = pipe(10, inc, dbl, str);

// Point-free: build a reusable composed function with `flow`.
export const describe: (n: number) => string = flow(inc, dbl, str);
```

`pipe` is Haskell's `&` (data-first); `flow` is Haskell's `.` (function-first). Both read left-to-right — the opposite of native TS call nesting.

```ts
import { pipe } from 'fp-ts/function';

const sum = (xs: ReadonlyArray<number>): number => xs.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);
const clampAt = (max: number) => (n: number): number => Math.min(n, max);
const toFixed = (digits: number) => (n: number): string => n.toFixed(digits);

export const summarise = (xs: ReadonlyArray<number>): string =>
  pipe(xs, sum, clampAt(100), toFixed(2));

// Equivalent without pipe, top-down reading order lost:
const nested = (xs: ReadonlyArray<number>): string =>
  toFixed(2)(clampAt(100)(sum(xs)));

export const _demo: readonly [string, string] = [
  summarise([10, 20, 30]),
  nested([10, 20, 30]),
];
```

Both implementations produce the same value — but `summarise` describes the pipeline in plain English order (sum, clamp, format), while `nested` forces the reader to parse inside-out.

Method chaining requires every intermediate to be a prototype method on the carrier type — you can't inject your own `trim` unless `String.prototype.trim` already exists. `pipe(a, f, g, h)` is data-first function application: any function that takes the previous step's output works, even ad-hoc ones you define inline.

