`tap` returns the same observable — it's for observation, not transformation. The v7+ object form `tap({ next, error, complete })` replaces the deprecated positional `tap(next, error, complete)`.

```ts
import { of, Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { tap, map } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Metric {
  readonly name: string;
  readonly value: number;
}

const source$: Observable<Metric> = of(
  { name: 'latency', value: 42 },
  { name: 'latency', value: 55 }
);

export const logged$: Observable<Metric> = source$.pipe(
  tap({
    next: (m: Metric) => console.log('[metric]', m.name, m.value),
    error: (e: unknown) => console.error('[metric] error', e),
    complete: () => console.log('[metric] complete'),
  }),
  map((m: Metric) => m)
);
```

Use `tap({ next, error, complete })`. The v7 object form supersedes the v6 positional `tap(nextFn, errFn, completeFn)`, which is now deprecated.

```ts
