The v7 `retry({ count, delay })` object form supersedes the deprecated `retryWhen`. Returning a `timer(ms)` from `delay` produces an exponential backoff purely by computing the delay off the attempt number.

```ts
import { Observable, timer } from "rxjs";
import { retry } from "rxjs/operators";

interface UserProfile {
  id: string;
  displayName: string;
}

declare function fetchProfile$(id: string): Observable<UserProfile>;

export function loadProfile$(id: string): Observable<UserProfile> {
  return fetchProfile$(id).pipe(
    retry({
      count: 4,
      delay: (_err: unknown, retryCount: number): Observable<number> =>
        timer(2 ** retryCount * 200),
    })
  );
}
```

If all four attempts fail, the original error is surfaced to the consumer unchanged.

In v7+, `retry({ count, delay })` encapsulates the same intent — bounded retries with a delay between each — without the awkward inner-error-observable dance of `retryWhen`.

```ts
import { Observable, timer } from "rxjs";
import { retry } from "rxjs/operators";

interface SyncResult {
  ok: boolean;
  syncedAt: number;
}

declare const source$: Observable<SyncResult>;

export const withFixedRetry$: Observable<SyncResult> = source$.pipe(
  retry({
    count: 3,
    delay: (): Observable<number> => timer(1000),
  })
);
```

`retryWhen` is deprecated because the nested observable gave consumers enough rope to accidentally resubscribe forever. The object form makes the retry budget explicit.

```ts
import { Observable, timer } from "rxjs";
import { retry } from "rxjs/operators";

interface HttpResponse {
  status: number;
  body: string;
}

declare function httpGet$(url: string): Observable<HttpResponse>;

export function fetchWithRetry$(url: string): Observable<HttpResponse> {
  return httpGet$(url).pipe(
    retry({
      count: 3,
      delay: (): Observable<number> => timer(500),
    })
  );
}
```

`count` replaces the manual scan-counter; `delay` replaces the inner pipe. The deprecated `retryWhen` operator is no longer required for the 99% case.

`retry(3)` retries up to three times but with zero delay — which typically just hammers the upstream and hits the same transient failure. Switch to the object form and supply an exponential `delay` callback.

```ts
import { Observable, timer } from "rxjs";
import { retry } from "rxjs/operators";

interface ApiResponse {
  data: string;
}

declare function callApi$(): Observable<ApiResponse>;

export const run$: Observable<ApiResponse> = callApi$().pipe(
  retry({
    count: 3,
    delay: (_err: unknown, attempt: number): Observable<number> =>
      timer(2 ** attempt * 300),
  })
);
```

First retry waits ~600 ms, then ~1200 ms, then ~2400 ms — enough to ride out brief blips without saturating the server.

Use `retry({ count, delay })` where `delay` is a callback returning an `Observable<number>` — typically `timer(ms)`.

```ts
import { Observable, timer } from "rxjs";
import { retry } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Payload {
  value: number;
}

declare const source$: Observable<Payload>;

export const retried$: Observable<Payload> = source$.pipe(
  retry({
    count: 5,
    delay: (_err: unknown, attempt: number): Observable<number> =>
      timer(2 ** attempt * 100),
  })
);
```

The callback receives the error and the 1-indexed attempt number, so the delay doubles each time: 200, 400, 800, 1600, 3200 ms.

Fold the inner pipe into the `delay` callback on `retry`.

```ts
import { Observable, timer } from "rxjs";
import { retry } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Ping {
  host: string;
  latencyMs: number;
}

declare const ping$: Observable<Ping>;

export const resilientPing$: Observable<Ping> = ping$.pipe(
